Title: Heart Attack

Overview:
- A heart attacks occurs when blood flow to a part of the heart is blocked.
- This blockage is usually caused by a buildup of fat, cholesterol, or other substances in the arteries.
- Without proper blood flow, the heart muscle can become damaged or die.
- It is a medical emergency that requires immediate attention.
- Early recognition and quick action can save lives.

Common Symptoms:
- Chest pain or discomfort, often described as pressure, tightness, or squeezing.
- Pain spreading to the arms (especially left arm), neck, jaw, or back.
- Shortness of breath.
- Sweating or cold sweat.
- Nausea or vomiting.
- Dizziness or lightheadedness.
- Unusual fatigue, especially in women.

Risk Factors:
- High blood pressure.
- High cholesterol levels.
- Smoking or tobacco use.
- Diabetes.
- Obesity or overweight.
- Lack of physical activity.
- Family history of heart disease.
- High stress levels and unhealthy lifestyle.

Basic Home Diagnosis (Preliminary Checks):
- Observe any sudden chest discomfort or pain lasting more than a few minutes.
- Check if pain spreads to other parts of the upper body.
- Monitor breathing difficulty or unusual sweating.
- Note associated symptoms like nausea, dizziness, or fatigue.
- Check pulse rate if possible.
- Do not ignore mild or unusual symptoms, especially in high-risk individuals.
- If symptoms suggest a heart attack, treat it as an emergency and seek immediate help.

Management and Prevention:
- Maintain a healthy diet low in saturated fats and cholesterol.
- Exercise regularly to keep the heart strong.
- Avoid smoking and limit alcohol consumption.
- Monitor blood pressure, cholesterol, and blood sugar levels.
- Manage stress through relaxation techniques.
- Maintain a healthy body weight.
- Take prescribed medications regularly if under treatment.
- Go for regular health checkups.

When to Seek Medical Help:
- Chest pain or discomfort lasting more than a few minutes.
- Pain spreading to arms, neck, jaw, or back.
- Severe shortness of breath.
- Sudden sweating, nausea, or dizziness.
- Loss of consciousness.
- Any suspected heart attack symptoms should be treated as an emergency.

Disclaimer:
- This information is for educational and awareness purposes only.
- It should not be used as a substitute for professional medical advice, diagnosis, or treatment.
- Always seek immediate medical attention in case of suspected heart attack.
